theologians, and doctors, Betancourt offers a new history of gender, sexuality, and race.Betancourt weaves together art, literature, and an impressive array of texts to investigate depictions of sexual consent in images of the Virgin Mary, tactics of sexual shaming in the story of Empress Theodora, narratives of transgender monks, portrayals of same-gender desire in images of the Doubting Thomas, and stereotypes of gender and ethnicity in representations of the Ethiopian Eunuch. He also gathers evidence from medical manuals detailing everything from surgical practices for late terminations of pregnancy to save a mother's life to a host of procedures used to affirm a person's gender.Showing how understandings of gender, sexuality, and race have long been enmeshed, Byzantine Intersectionality offers a groundbreaking look at the culture of the medieval world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIntersectionality (Sociology)zByzantine Empire. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aActs of the Apostles.  aAnnunciation.  aAveril Cameron.  aByzantine Matters.  aByzantine art.  aByzantium.  aDoubting Thomas.  aEmpress Theodora.  aEthiopian Eunuch.  aIncredulity of Thomas.  aProcopius.  aSecret History.  aVirgin Mary.  aabortion.  acis.  aconsent.  aeunuchs.  agender affirmation.  agender fluid.  agender fluidity.  agender identity.  agender nonconforming.  agender nonconformity.  agender stereotypes.  agender.  aintersectionality.  amedieval.  apregnancy termination.  aqueer desire.  aqueer sexuality.  aqueer.  arace in the medieval world.  arace.  aracialized difference.  aracialized stereotypes.  areproductive rights.  asame-gender desire.  asame-sex desire.  asexual consent.  asexuality.  aslut shaming.  atrans.  atransgender history.